Certainly! Here's an example of a PowerShell script that updates an XML file:

```powershell
# Function to update XML content
function Update-XmlContent {
    param (
        [string]$xmlFilePath,
        [string]$elementName,
        [string]$newContent
    )

    # Load the XML file
    [xml]$xml = Get-Content $xmlFilePath

    # Find the element by name
    $targetElement = $xml.SelectSingleNode("//${elementName}")

    if ($targetElement -ne $null) {
        # Update the content of the element
        $targetElement.InnerText = $newContent
    } else {
        # If the element is not found, you can handle it accordingly
        Write-Host "Element '$elementName' not found in the XML file."
    }

    # Save the updated XML file
    $xml.Save($xmlFilePath)
}

# Example usage
$xmlFilePath = "C:\Path\To\Your\File.xml"
$elementName = "existingElement"
$newContent = "Updated Content"

Update-XmlContent -xmlFilePath $xmlFilePath -elementName $elementName -newContent $newContent
```

Replace `"C:\Path\To\Your\File.xml"`, `"existingElement"`, and `"Updated Content"` with your XML file path, the name of the element you want to update, and the new content you want to set, respectively.

This script uses the `[xml]` type accelerator to load the XML file and then selects the target element using XPath. It updates the content of the element and saves the changes back to the original XML file.
